 a situation that threatens to reduce music to a cheap, abundant resource. By interrogating the tensions between streaming’s benefits and pitfalls, Drott sheds light on music’s situation within digital capitalism, from growing concentrations of monopoly power and music’s use in corporate surveillance to issues of musical value, labor, and artist pay.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aMusic and the Internet. 0aMusic tradexTechnological innovations. 0aSound recording industry. 0aStreaming audio. 7aMUSIC / Business Aspects.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027874?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027874423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027874/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles